item.l: Vase made of pale blue jasper ware with white reliefs; oviform body flattened on the shoulders; domed cover with figure of Pegasus on top resting on a pale pink cloud; on one side the crowning of a poet, and on the other an altar, palm tree, Athene in temple, and vases; olive wreath on neck of vase; honeysuckle and other ornaments on lower part; handles, in the form of two serpents disputing an egg, springing from Gorgon masks; square plinth with meander on the sides.
Wedgwood, Josiah to The British Museum
Impressed with two marks resembling double leaves.
Vase and cover; porcelain; upper area decorated with frieze of lions and grotesque masks; caryatid handles on either side; known as the Newstead Vase.
Paget, F Howard to The British Museum

Vase ('vase d'Entrecolles'), cast in hard-paste porcelain ('pte nouvelle'), a bulbous body on a flared foot decorated in two shades of green and in white on a celadon ground. Four circular medallions in pte-sur-pte depicting landmarks in Paris hang from a garland of flowers around the neck; each medallion is enclosed in a cartouche containing a ship, the emblem of Paris, and surmounted by a gateway. Between these are pale green laurel-leaf garlands incorporating the dates of major events in the history of Paris; round the rim a band of dolphins with the city's motto. The decoration is all executed in low relief, the interior is white; the foot is made separately and attached to the body with a metal fitting.
France, Government of to The British Museum
acquisition (through intermediary) donated through ministre de l'instruction publique
The T and D ligatured and incorporated into the design.

Vase (vase Chevilly); hard-paste porcelain (porcelaine nouvelle), of square section, tapering; thin neck springing from rounded shoulders; two handles in the form of overlapping vetch leaves; covered with crystalline glaze in shades of cream and buff; the crystals occur in patches on the surface of the glaze; handles glazed; maker's mark.
Scott, John M to The British Museum
Printed in grey within a triangle.
Vase; clear glass, mould-blown with polished rim, vertical walls with fluid curves forming a sinuous outline.
Rosenthal Studio Haus to The British Museum
